.TH ELFBRK 1 "2026-05-11" "elfbrk 0.3a" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
elfbrk \- ELF32/ELF64 file format fuzzer, analyzer, and steganography tool
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B elfbrk
.I elf_file
.RI [ options\ .\|.\|. ]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B elfbrk
reads an ELF32 or ELF64 binary into memory and performs analysis or in-place
modification depending on the flags supplied.
Multiple flags can be combined in a single invocation.
Analysis flags are read-only and safe on any file.
Write flags modify the file in place \(em work on a copy.
.PP
Class (32-bit vs 64-bit) is auto-detected from
.BR EI_CLASS .
All offset and size arithmetic uses
.B uint64_t
internally to avoid overflow.
Bounds checking is applied to every structure access before dereferencing.
.SH OPTIONS
.SS Analysis
.TP
.B \-\-help\fR, \fB\-h\fR, \fB/?
Print a usage summary and exit.
.TP
.B \-\-phdr
Walk and print all program headers (segments).
Shows type, file offset, virtual/physical address, file size, memory size,
flags, and alignment.
.TP
.B \-\-shdr
Walk and print all section headers.
Resolves section names from
.IR .shstrtab .
Shows index, name, type, address, file offset, size, flags, and alignment.
.TP
.B \-\-slack\-count
Enumerate every location in the file where data can be hidden without
affecting execution.
Shows hex content for each region and prints a category summary at the end.
.RS
.TP 14
.B [ehdr]
.BR EI_OSABI ,
.BR EI_ABIVERSION ,
.B EI_PAD
(9 bytes),
.B e_version
(4 bytes),
.B e_flags
if zero.
.TP
.B [phdr]
.B p_paddr
per segment \(em physical address field, ignored by the kernel on all
virtual-memory OSes.
.TP
.B [phdr]
.B PT_NOTE
segment content \(em kernel maps but never validates.
.TP
.B [shdr]
.BR sh_link ,
.BR sh_info ,
.B sh_entsize
on sections where the loader does not use those fields.
.TP
.B [gap]
Alignment padding between sections in the file.
.TP
.B [over]
Bytes past the last section / table (EOF overlay).
.RE
.TP
.B \-\-paddr\-read
Hex dump every
.B p_paddr
field from all program headers.
.TP
.BI \-\-paddr\-read\-file \ file
Extract all
.B p_paddr
bytes \(em concatenated in segment order \(em and write them raw to
.IR file .
Symmetric with
.BR \-\-paddr\-write\-file .
.TP
.BI \-\-slack\-read\-file \ file
Collect every slack region, read their bytes in file-offset order, and write
the concatenated result to
.IR file .
Always produces the same number of bytes as the total slack capacity.
Symmetric with
.BR \-\-slack\-write\-file .
.SS Steganography \(em p_paddr fields
.TP
.BI \-\-paddr\-write \ hexstring
Pack bytes from a hex string across the
.B p_paddr
fields of the program headers in order.
.B p_paddr
is ignored by the kernel on any OS with virtual memory.
Bytes are packed left-to-right; the last partially-filled field is
zero-padded.
Accepts bare pairs or colon-, dash-, or space-separated bytes.
Total capacity is
.RI ( e_phnum " \(mu 4)"
bytes on ELF32,
.RI ( e_phnum " \(mu 8)"
bytes on ELF64.
These bytes land in process memory at runtime because the phdr table is
mapped by
.BR PT_PHDR .
.TP
.BI \-\-paddr\-write\-file \ file
Same as
.B \-\-paddr\-write
but reads the payload from
.IR file .
Useful for binary payloads such as shellcode, keys, or compressed data.
.SS Steganography \(em slack regions
.TP
.BI \-\-slack\-write\-file \ file
Write the contents of
.I file
into the binary's slack regions in file-offset order, scattering bytes
across as many regions as needed.
Reports payload size, total slack capacity, bytes written, overflow (if
payload exceeds capacity), and unused bytes remaining.
.PP
.B \-\-slack\-write\-file
and
.B \-\-slack\-read\-file
operate on the same regions in the same order.
A write followed by a read recovers the payload exactly.
.SS Section and note manipulation
.TP
.B \-\-shdr\-strip
Zeros
.BR e_shoff ,
.BR e_shnum ,
and
.B e_shstrndx
in the ELF header.
The binary continues to execute normally \(em the kernel only uses the
program header table at load time.
Tools that depend on section headers
.RB ( "readelf \-S" ,
.BR objdump ,
.BR gdb )
lose all section visibility.
.TP
.BI \-\-note\-inject \ file
Write the contents of
.I file
into the first
.B PT_NOTE
segment, bounded by that segment's
.BR p_filesz .
The segment header and surrounding structure are untouched.
The binary continues to execute normally \(em the kernel maps PT_NOTE
segments read-only but never validates their content.
Reports bytes written and remaining capacity.
.SS Debug section manipulation
.TP
.B \-\-debuglink\-corrupt
Flips all bits in the CRC32 field of
.IR .gnu_debuglink .
GDB validates this CRC before loading a separate
.B .debug
file \(em a corrupted CRC causes it to silently refuse symbol loading.
Prints the old and new CRC values.
.TP
.BI \-\-debuglink\-path \ path
Replaces the filename string in
.I .gnu_debuglink
with
.IR path .
The new path must fit within the existing section (at most
.I section_size\ \-\ 5
bytes).
The existing CRC is preserved at the new aligned offset.
Use to redirect debuggers to a nonexistent or poisoned debug file.
.TP
.BI \-\-build\-id\-patch \ hexstring
Overwrites the build ID descriptor bytes in
.I .note.gnu.build-id
with the supplied hex bytes.
Build IDs are used by GDB,
.BR eu-debuginfod ,
and crash reporters to fetch matching debug info \(em a wrong ID breaks
that chain.
Prints old and new ID bytes.
.TP
.BI \-\-debug\-inject \ section\ file
Writes the contents of
.I file
into the named section, bounded by that section's size.
Remainder is zero-padded.
Works on any section by name.
Intended for injecting malformed or misleading DWARF into
.IR .debug_info ,
.IR .debug_line ,
etc.
The binary continues to execute normally.
.TP
.B \-\-debug\-zero
Zeroes the content of every section whose name starts with
.IR .debug_ .
Section headers are left intact so the binary still appears to have debug
sections, but their content is gone.
Confuses tools such as Valgrind, perf, and sanitizers that consume DWARF
directly rather than through GDB.
.SS Magic patch
Overwrite the first 4 bytes of the ELF header
.RB ( "e_ident[0..3]" )
with an alternate signature.
Useful for bypassing naive file-type detection.
.PP
.TS
l l l .
\fB\-\-magic\-patch\fR	0xBADC0DE0	elfbrk signature
\fB\-\-magic\-patch\-reset\fR	0x7F454C46	restore ELF magic
\fB\-\-magic\-patch\-slack\fR	0x90909090	NOP sled pattern
\fB\-\-magic\-patch\-pk1\fR	0x504B0304	ZIP local file header
\fB\-\-magic\-patch\-pk2\fR	0x504B0506	ZIP end of central directory
\fB\-\-magic\-patch\-pk3\fR	0x504B0708	ZIP data descriptor
\fB\-\-magic\-patch\-zb1\fR	0x4D530304	zipbrk variant 1
\fB\-\-magic\-patch\-zb2\fR	0x4D530506	zipbrk variant 2
\fB\-\-magic\-patch\-zb3\fR	0x4D530708	zipbrk variant 3
\fB\-\-magic\-patch\-dos\fR	0x4D5A4CCC	DOS MZ header
.TE
.SH OUTPUT FORMAT
All output uses a pipe-bordered style
.RB ( "|  ..." ).
The ELF header dump is always printed at the end of every run reflecting
the current on-disk state.
.B Total Slack Space
is reported in the summary block when
.B \-\-slack\-count
is passed.
.SH NOTES
.IP \(bu 3
ELF32 and ELF64 are both supported.
Class is auto-detected from
.BR EI_CLASS .
.IP \(bu 3
The section header table is not used by the kernel at load time.
.B \-\-shdr\-strip
and the
.B [shdr]
entries in
.B \-\-slack\-count
exploit this.
.IP \(bu 3
.B p_paddr
fields are inside the mapped
.B PT_PHDR
segment \(em payload written there is present in process memory at runtime
without touching the file again.
.IP \(bu 3
.B \-\-slack\-read\-file
and
.B \-\-slack\-write\-file
use a fixed region ordering (sorted by file offset) so they are always
symmetric regardless of what has been written.
.IP \(bu 3
No dependencies beyond libc.
Build with:
.B gcc \-Wall \-Wextra \-o elfbrk elfbrk.c
.SH EXAMPLES
.TP
Print all program headers:
.B elfbrk ./binary \-\-phdr
.TP
Enumerate slack space with hex content:
.B elfbrk ./binary \-\-slack\-count
.TP
Hide a payload in p_paddr fields:
.B elfbrk ./binary \-\-paddr\-write deadbeefcafebabe
.TP
Scatter a file across all slack regions:
.B elfbrk ./binary \-\-slack\-write\-file payload.bin
.TP
Recover it:
.B elfbrk ./binary \-\-slack\-read\-file recovered.bin
.TP
Corrupt the debug link CRC and strip section headers:
.B elfbrk ./binary \-\-debuglink\-corrupt \-\-shdr\-strip
.TP
Disguise as a ZIP file then restore:
.EX
elfbrk ./binary \-\-magic\-patch\-pk1
elfbrk ./binary \-\-magic\-patch\-reset
.EE
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR readelf (1),
.BR objdump (1),
.BR gdb (1),
.BR file (1),
.BR eu-readelf (1)
